@node a3091 "Controller"
@toc toc
@{u}@{b}A3000: A3091@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}·@{ub} I recommend to replace the originally old Western Digital WD 00-04 PROTO controller with the newer, fixed one 00-08.

@{b}·@{ub} Also you should check if pin 25 of the external SCSI connector has +5V, otherwise you suffer from the wrong-way diode. This part was put in the wrong way and  so can not terminate the SCSI chain correctly.

@{b}·@{ub} I savere cases you should @{b}not@{ub} terminate the drive! I experienced lots of SCSI bus lockups when my drive was terminated, switching of the termination (by accident) solved this problem.

@{b}·@{ub} On A3000 with V36 bootroms the well known problem of the delayed boot exists also for the ZIP drive. Simply put a disk in the drive, and the A3000 will boot up quickly.

@{b}·@{ub} If there was no disk in the drive during startup, the drive is also unknown to the DOS. Use SCSIMounter or similar to mount it for the first time. Afterwards you should have no trouble with diskchanges.

@endnode


@node scsiprep "Preping and formating"
@toc toc
@{u}@{b}Preping and formatting the disk@{uu}@{ub}
@{b}·@{ub} If you have connected the drive, inserted a disk (may be preformatted for IBM or Macintosh, doesn't matter) and powered up your amiga, you should see the device in your HD-Prep program like@{i}HDToolsBox@{ui}. (It's assumed your're using this one, if not your actual readouts may differ) The device is currently unknown to you Amiga filing system, it's not in the file drive specifications. So you should read out the @{" drive specifications " link ds}. Now your Amiga knows about the new drive.

@{b}·@{ub} You may then format the inserted disk with a simple format command. Several people reported, that low-level formatting gains some speed out of the disks, but I can not found any proof of it, accept in the Diskspeed 4.2-results. So if you like to low level format your disks, stay within the@{i}HDToolsBox@{ui}, select @{b}Low Level Format@{ub} and accept the destruction of all your data. Than wait for approx. 10 Minutes.

@{b}·@{ub} Newer ZIP-drives come with a Zip-Tools disk that is write protected. In this case you can use the low-level format to get rid of this protection. Another way is to use the ZIP-Tools for the Amiga or try to use them on a PC or Macintosh.

@{b}·@{ub} The AmigaOS has several problems dealing with removeables. (They may be fixed by the driver, but don't count on that!) If you have no disk inserted during startup, the drive simply is not there. You must than mount it using SCSIMounter or similar tools. Also it has difficulties dealing with different partitioned removeable media. If the next disk is partitioned different from the first, this could lead you into trouble. The least worst case is, that you have some ghost-icons and entries for the now removed partitions. The worst case is, that the OS keeps the partitioninformation and destroyes your current disk. The problem may(!) be solved, if you choose to write a real RDB to the ZIP-Disk, but it is a known probelme of several controllers not to work with RDBs written by other controllers. You may find yourself dealing with unreadable disks at your friends computer.

@{b}·@{ub} @{b}That's why I recommend, that you @{" partition your zip disks " link pertzip} all the same: one big partition.@{ub} I find the following most convinient: I format my disk al the same as one big partition of ~95MB. With a tool i read out a sample @{" ZIP mountlist " link zipmount} that i put than in @{i}DEVS:DOSDrivers/@{ui}. This garanties, that the drive is known to the system under all conditions even if no disk is inserted upon startup (which of course took unnaturaly long on an A3000 with V36 bootroms, of course)

@{b}·@{ub} Formatting new disks is done easy: If you like a low level format, do so within @{i}HDToolsBox@{ui} or your special program for this action. Then start the @{i}System/Format@{ui} program, if you do not see an icon on the workbench for your ZIP disk (if you low level formatted the disk, you should see one, otherwise if you simply inserted a Macintosh or IBM preformatted disk, you should not). The Format program shows you a list of all acceptible devices, there will be an entry for the ZIP disk also. Select it, choose your options and go for it. Formatting will take about 5-10 minutes. Though your device is ever named @{i}ZIP0@{ui} - or whatever you choose for a name within @{i}HDToolsBox@{ui} - you may rename the logical device name to whatever you like it to.

@{b}·@{ub} If your are using a SCSI uitility, that can read out the data from the drive - like @{" ProbeSCSI " link zipprobe} does you may be surprised about the high number of bad/remapped blocks. First of all, remember the disk is floppy disk technology based and you do have often bad blocks on floppies too. This is a normal behavior. Secondd, take a closer look and you will see, that a lot of the marked block constist of pure humbug values either 0 or in the millions were no physical block exists. So @{b}real@{ub} bad block counts from 20-40 are a normal value, don't get nervous.

@endnode

