@node speedct "Speed comparisons"
@toc toc
@font topaz.font 11
@{u}@{b}Speed comparisons:@{uu}@{ub}

The benchmark-program @{i}CTHDBENCH@{ui} test the drives in a 30MB partition under DOS. Only under the non-multitasking DOS in Real-mode you have the full control over the computer timing, also no system enhancers were loaded, @{i}autoexec.bat@{ui} and  @{i}config.sys@{ui} were empty. The test was done using a 486-66-CPU with EISA-SCSI adaptor Adaptec 1742.

All modern disk storage systems are using some kind of ZoneBitRecording ZBR that stores more sectros on the piuter areas of the disk and less sectros on the inner areas. Reading more sectors in a single rotations means higher data throughput, reading less means lower throughput. That's what measured for the fastest/slowest zone. On dreives with only one Head the speed layout of these zone has it's lowest points not on the borders, but in the center of the graphic representation.


Benchmarks	(Cthdbench, 100-MByte-Disk)

		fastest Zone	slowest Zone
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Max. Read	925 KByte/s	625 KByte/s
Max. Write	927 KByte/s	623 KByte/s
Average 	538 KByte/s	388 KByte/s
Total time	12:17 min:s	16:56 min:s

@endnode

